title: Tools-Suite: v2.0
body:
Issue overview
--------------
Goal of v2.0 of the suite would be to remove all references to the Nan-bindings and move forward with creating a more publicly usable third party web assembly library. This will include enhanced documentation and examples. Additionally we want to be able to maintain the library in a way that keeps up with the latest changes to WebAssembly.

Below are the steps we should take (in order):
1. Update compilation/build workflow (Omer)
2. Fix and verify C++ unit test integrity (Mark)
3. Created Archived, read-only AMO-Tools-Suite repo from existing (Omer) 
4. Create new repo for actively developed Suite repo - will be renamed (Gina, Omer)
5. Update library used for js unit tests (Nick protoype + intern)
6. Update doxygen related to wasm bindings

body:
new attribute to add to calculateFanAttributes

To calculate wet bulb temperature (if that isn't an input)
Inputs: dryBulb, relativeHumidity,baroP

Step 1:  Calculate Humidity ratio (as a function of dry bulb, relative humidity, barometric Pressure) 
use: humidityRatioNormal = calculateRatioRH(dryBulb, relativeHumidity,barometricPressure)

Step 2: set first guess for wetBulb = dryBulb

Step 3: Calculate humidity ratio again (this time as a function of dry bulb and wet bulb)
use: humidityRatioNew = calculateRelativeHumidityFromWetBulb(dryBulb, wetBulb,baroP)

Step 4: Start loop, exit criteria = (humidityRatioNew  - humidityRatioNormal) / humidityRatioNormal) > 0.00001
Loop Step 1: Calculate humidity ratio again (this time as a function of dry bulb and wet bulb - 0.001)
humidityRatioNew2 = calculateRelativeHumidityFromWetBulb(dryBulb, wetBulb-0.001,baroP)

Loop Step 2: calculate new wetBulb Temp
dw_dtwb = (humidityRatioNew - humidityRatioNew2 ) / 0.001
        wetBulb = wetBulb - (humidityRatioNew - humidityRatioNormal) / dw_dtwb

Loop Step 3: calculate new "humidityRatioNew"
humidityRatioNew = calculateRelativeHumidityFromWetBulb(dryBulb, wetBulb,baroP)

Loop until the criteria is met
Step 5: Add wetBulb to the fan attributes return object (if the method == wetBulb, just return the user input)



Original code, I think in C#
```
Function Wet_bulb(Tdb, RH, P)
' Calculates the Wet Bulb temp given dry blub temp [degC] and Relative Humidity
' Uses Newton-Rhapson iteration to converge quickly
'   Tdb = Dry bulb temperature [degC]
'   RH = Relative humidity ratio [Fraction or %]
'   P = Ambient Pressure [kPa]

    W_normal = Hum_rat2(Tdb, RH, P)
    Wet_bulb = Tdb
    ' Solve to within 0.001% accuracy using Newton-Rhapson
    W_new = Hum_rat(Tdb, Wet_bulb, P)
    Do While Abs((W_new - W_normal) / W_normal) > 0.00001
        W_new2 = Hum_rat(Tdb, Wet_bulb - 0.001, P)
        dw_dtwb = (W_new - W_new2) / 0.001
        Wet_bulb = Wet_bulb - (W_new - W_normal) / dw_dtwb
        W_new = Hum_rat(Tdb, Wet_bulb, P)
    Loop
End Function
```

title: Latent heat of fuel
body:
Issue overview
--------------
Can we use the Steam properties calculator to estimate the enthalpy of water vapor in combustion?


Issue details
--------------
From Keith Woodbury 2012/01/23
  Regarding the latent heat loss:  I think the key is the approximation of the enthalpy of the water vapor in the exhaust.  The thermodynamic state of the vapor is highly superheated, but at the very low partial pressure of the water vapor in the exhaust.  For a practical ranges of fuels and %O2 in stack, the pressure of water vapor in the stack is between 0.5 and 2.0 psia.  Arvind approximates the enthalpy of the water vapor as SATURATED VAPOR at the PARTIAL PRESSURE of the vapor.  This does not take into account the variation of enthalpy  of the vapor with temperature (for low pressure ideal gases, such as air or water in atmospheric conditions, temperature, not pressure, is the main driver).    I did a few calculations in a spreadsheet (below) to illustrate the approximations.  
  Also shown in the table (AIAC) are our internal representation for enthalpy of vapor in the stack.  We presently ignore the pressure dependence, and only use the enthalpy of SATURATED VAPOR at the STACK GAS TEMPERTURE.  It appears that at higher temperatures (beyond typical for boiler stack but not, perhaps, for high temperature furnaces), the effect of pressure becomes more important.

Thanks again for your help,
Keith Woodbury

title: Latent heat of fuel
body:
Issue overview
--------------
Can we use the Steam properties calculator to estimate the enthalpy of water vapor in combustion?


Issue details
--------------
From Keith Woodbury 2012/01/23
  Regarding the latent heat loss:  I think the key is the approximation of the enthalpy of the water vapor in the exhaust.  The thermodynamic state of the vapor is highly superheated, but at the very low partial pressure of the water vapor in the exhaust.  For a practical ranges of fuels and %O2 in stack, the pressure of water vapor in the stack is between 0.5 and 2.0 psia.  Arvind approximates the enthalpy of the water vapor as SATURATED VAPOR at the PARTIAL PRESSURE of the vapor.  This does not take into account the variation of enthalpy  of the vapor with temperature (for low pressure ideal gases, such as air or water in atmospheric conditions, temperature, not pressure, is the main driver).    I did a few calculations in a spreadsheet (below) to illustrate the approximations.  
  Also shown in the table (AIAC) are our internal representation for enthalpy of vapor in the stack.  We presently ignore the pressure dependence, and only use the enthalpy of SATURATED VAPOR at the STACK GAS TEMPERTURE.  It appears that at higher temperatures (beyond typical for boiler stack but not, perhaps, for high temperature furnaces), the effect of pressure becomes more important.

Thanks again for your help,
Keith Woodbury

title: Water Assessment Bindings and Methods
body:
Issue overview
--------------
Below is a series of MEASUR inputs => SUITE outputs we need to implement for the water assessment.  If it matters, these are going to be accessed similarly to PHAST losses. i.e. I am entering 4 process uses in measur, iterating through each, processing, sending to suite, and back.

Basic math, but the team would like implemented in suite for consistency. Math is from Kristina but I have changed property names. Let me know if you have questions.

## Process Use
Inputs

```tsx
export interface ProcessUse {
    waterRequired: number,
    waterConsumed: number,
    waterLossInput: number,
    hoursPerYear: number,
    // annual production units
    annualProduction: number
    fractionGrossWaterRecirculated: number,
}
```

Results

```tsx
export interface ProcessUseResults {
    recirculatedWater: number,
    incomingWater: number,
    wasteDischargedAndRecycledOther: number,
}

```

grossWaterUse = waterRequired
- reciruclatedWater = grossWaterUse * fractionGrossWaterRecirculated
- incomingWater = grossWaterUse  reciruclatedWater = grossWaterUse * (1  fractionGrossWaterRecirculated)
- wasteDischargedAndRecycledOther= incomingWater  waterConsumed  waterLoss
---
## Cooling Tower

Inputs

```tsx
export interface CoolingTower {
    hoursPerYear: number,
    tonnage: number
    loadFactor: number,
    evaporationRateDegree: number,
    temperatureDrop: number,
    makeupConductivity: number,
    blowdownConductivity: number,
}
```

Results

```tsx

export interface CoolingTowerResults {
    grossWaterUse: number,
    evaporationLoss: number,
    cycleOfConcentration: number,
    makeupWater: number,
    blowdownLoss: number,
}

```

- grossWaterUse= 3 * tonnage* loadFactor* 60 * hoursPerYear
- evaporationLoss= (evaporationRateDegree/10) * temperatureDrop* grossWaterUse
- cycleOfConcentration= blowdownConductivity/ makeupConductivity
- makeupWater= evaporationLoss / (1  (1/cycleOfConcentration))
- blowdownLoss = makeupWater  evaporationLoss

---

## Boiler Water

Inputs

```tsx
export interface BoilerWater {
    hoursPerYear: number,
    power: number
    loadFactor: number,
    steamPerPower: number,
    feedwaterConductivity: number,
    makeupConductivity: number,
    blowdownConductivity: number,
}
```

Results

```tsx

export interface BoilerWaterResults {
    cycleOfConcentration: number,
    grossWaterUse: number,
    makeupWater: number,
    steamLoss: number,
    blowdownLoss: number,
    condensateReturn: number,
    rateOfRecirculation: number
}


```

- cycleOfConcentration = blowdownConductivity/ feedwaterConductivity
- grossWaterUse = operatingHours * power * loadFactor * 0.002 * 60 * steamPerPower / (1  (1/cycleOfConcentration)) {not sure what 0.002 is, probably density in lb/gal}
- makeupWater = (feedwaterConductivity/makeupWaterConductivity) * grossWaterUse
- blowdownLoss = (1/cycleOfConcentration) * grossWaterUse
- steamLoss = makeupWater  blowdownLoss
- condensateReturn = (1  (feedwaterConductivity/makeupWaterConductivity)) * grossWaterUse
- rateOfRecirculation = makeupWater/grossWater

---

## Kitchen and Restroom

Inputs

```tsx
export interface KitchenRestroom {
    employeeCount: number,
    workdaysPerYear: number,
    dailyUsePerEmployee: number
}
```

Results

```tsx
grossWaterUse = employeeCount* workdaysPerYear* dailyUsePerEmployee

```
---

## Landscaping

Inputs

```tsx
export interface Landscaping {
    areaIrrigated: number,
    yearlyInchesIrrigated: number,
}
```

- areaIrrigated (in ft2 or m2)
- yearlyInchesIrrigated (in in or cm, convert to ft or m)

Results

```tsx
grossWaterUse = areaIrrigated * yearlyInchesIrrigated (in ft3 or m3, convert to gal for imp)

```
---
## Heat Energy in Discharge (Embodied Energy tab)

Inputs:

```
export interface HeatEnergyInputs {
    incomingTemp: number,
    outgoingTemp: number,
    heaterEfficiency: number,
    heatingFuelType: number,
    wasteWaterDischarge: number
}
```

Results

heatEnergy = wasteWaterDischarge * (outgoingTemp  incomingTemp) * 1 * 8.3454 * heatingEfficiency/1000000

---

## Added Motor Energy

```tsx
export interface MotorEnergy {
    numberUnits: number,
    hoursPerYear: number,
    ratedPower: number,
    loadFactor: number,
    systemEfficiency: number,
}
```

Results

energyUse = ratedPower * numberUnits * motorLoadFactor * operatingHours/systemEfficiency
